            "answer_text": "Thanks for the A2A Narayan Brahmachari. Many years back, I visited my neighbor's hometown for some reason which I don't remember. One afternoon, I was very hungry that I was served lunch first on a banana leaf and later for others. They served me rice, sambar, beetroot poriyal and potato fry. Poriyal is a sauted vegetable dish. [1] I hate beetroot so I ate it first and relished eating the potato fry next.  Image of Beetroot poriyal [2] On seeing the beetroot missing, people there thought I liked it a lot and served second round of it. One can never say no to them, such is the hospitality of Tamil people. Again, with so much of difficulty, I was stuffing it in my mouth and chewing it, people were like wow.. Moni likes Blood poriyal a lot. It was then I came to know that it was blood poriyal and not beetroot poriyal and I was like  Generally, blood poriyal is made with goat\u2019s blood, that people get it fresh from meat stalls and what I ate was the same too.  This is how the blood poriyal they served looked like [3] Process of doing it is very simple. Pour a few table spoons of oil in a kadai, temper it with mustard and broken urad dal, then saute it with onions, pour the blood and saute it well until the blood crumples dry. At last add grated coconut before getting it off from the stove. I'm not sure about nutritional values. But I had heard people saying blood is a good source of protein and people who cannot afford to eat meat, cook this blood regularly. This dish is so common in rural areas. Apart from this, There is a temple in TN where once in a year they used to celebrate a festival where the slaughtered animal's blood, mixed with boiled rice and served as prasadham. Women who cannot conceive, visit this temple during this festival with a belief that this prasadham could make them fertile. Footnotes[1] Poriyal - Wikipedia[2] beetroot poriyal - Google Search[3] Blood Fry Till You Die - My Tryst With South Indian \u2018Comfort Food\u2019",
