            },
            "answer_text": "It already is used in certain cuisines: boudin noir in France, for example, is blood sausage and the same exists in British cuisine as black pudding. Blood is high in vitamin A and contains iron and protein. When made into boudin, it may also be mixed with things like salt, fat, oatmeal, sugar and condiments although the French tend to like it best without anything much added. Pig blood is the base and since most people cannot get fresh blood, dried blood is used, having to be reconstituted with water, one part blood to six of water. Boudin is boiled initially to set the blood. It is rather rich to eat and not to the taste of all! It may be fried or grilled. In France it is served often over mashed potato and/or with cooked apples. It is also much loved in Italy, Spain, Portugal and South America and has a long history. It was been around since Roman times so, around 2000 years at least. ",
